{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "12 — Persistence & the Store Seam",
  "description": "Every turn Balaur speaks is written to the messages collection forever, but the model only ever sees a bounded recent window. This tour teaches that split — persistence is not context — through the master conversation singleton, the origin tagging that keeps runtime artifacts out of the model's eye, the compaction boundary that lets a years-long thread stay manageable, and the audit log that records every consequential write. It then defines what internal/store is allowed to be: a narrow seam for cross-cutting concerns only (audit, owner settings, LLM config, time), while domain packages talk to PocketBase directly in their own package.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "internal/conversation/conversation.go",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "12.1 — Persistence is not context",
      "description": "The package comment states the central invariant directly:\n\n> **PERSISTENCE IS NOT CONTEXT.** Every turn is stored forever in the messages collection; the model sees only the last few text turns (`RecentTurns`).\n\nThis is a deliberate product decision, not a storage optimisation. A years-long companion relationship accumulates far more turns than any model context window can hold. The solution is not to truncate or discard — it is to separate the two concerns:\n\n- **Persistence**: every turn, every role, every tool round, every runtime artefact — stored permanently in the `messages` PocketBase collection, inspectable in SQLite at any time.\n- **Context**: a small, filtered, chronological window of recent user/assistant text turns assembled fresh for each model call by `RecentTurns`.\n\nDurable facts that should survive context limits belong in approved **memories** (`internal/knowledge`) — that is what makes compaction safe: the gist moves forward in the summary, the detail lives in memories.\n\nAGENTS.md rule: *context is transparent — durable state lives in PocketBase collections (inspectable SQLite) and exported Markdown, never hidden in-session state.*"
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/conversation/conversation.go",
      "line": 44,
      "title": "12.2 — The master singleton",
      "description": "```go\nfunc Master(app core.App) (*core.Record, error)\n```\n\nThere is exactly one open master conversation: one companion, one continuous thread. This is a product decision, not a technical limit — switchable personas (heads) share this single thread; they change voice and tool-group, not history.\n\n`Master` implements create-or-find with a **lost-race retry**:\n\n1. Try to find an existing `kind='master' && status='open'` record.\n2. If none, create one with `app.Save`.\n3. If that save fails — a concurrent request may have won the race and already inserted the row — retry the find once. If the row now exists, return it; otherwise propagate the original error.\n\nThis avoids a UNIQUE-constraint failure producing an error the caller must handle. Two concurrent HTTP requests racing to start a fresh install both reach the same record, and only one write lands in the WAL.\n\nAGENTS.md note: `app.Save` bypasses PocketBase collection API rules by design. Code that writes on the owner's behalf is trusted — this is a feature, not a bug."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/conversation/conversation.go",
      "line": 73,
      "title": "12.3 — Compaction: folding the past",
      "description": "```go\nfunc CompactedThrough(conv *core.Record) time.Time\n```\n\nA companion relationship that lasts years produces more turns than any context window can hold. Manual compaction is the shipped answer: the owner folds earlier turns into the `conversations.summary` field and advances `compacted_through` — a `DateTime` field that acts as a **sliding read boundary**.\n\n`CompactedThrough` returns that boundary (zero time means nothing has been compacted yet). `RecentTurns` (step 12.4) uses it as a filter: turns *at or before* the boundary are excluded from context — the rolling summary carries their gist instead.\n\nCritically, the original turn records are **never deleted**. The owner can always open `pb_data/data.db` in a SQLite viewer and read the full history. Compaction moves the live view and the model context window forward; it does not erase the record. This preserves the transparency invariant even across a compacted boundary."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/conversation/conversation.go",
      "line": 88,
      "title": "12.4 — Appending turns by origin",
      "description": "```go\nfunc AppendOrigin(app core.App, conversationID string, msg llm.Message, toolName, origin string) error\n```\n\n`Append` is the zero-origin form (regular chat turns). `AppendOrigin` tags the record with an `origin` string that lets downstream code distinguish *why* a turn was written:\n\n- `\"\"` — a normal chat exchange initiated by the owner.\n- `\"nudge\"`, `\"briefing\"` — agent-initiated turns from background jobs (`internal/tasks/nudge.go`, `internal/tasks/briefing.go`); the UI polls for these so they surface in the chat pane without a page reload.\n- `\"uncommitted\"` (`OriginUncommitted`) — an assistant reply the honesty check caught claiming a capture no tool actually performed, where self-repair also failed. Kept in the record so the owner sees what was said; **barred from context** so the model never learns to imitate the unbacked claim.\n- `\"check\"` (`OriginCheck`) — the runtime's own honesty note, appended by `internal/turn` after a caught fabrication, similarly excluded from context.\n\nOnly the two constants `OriginUncommitted` and `OriginCheck` are declared in this file (lines 36–39); `\"nudge\"` and `\"briefing\"` are plain string literals at their job call sites. The `origin` field is also the idempotency hook for background jobs: a nudge job can query for existing nudge turns in the current period before deciding whether to emit another.\n\nTool payloads land in a dedicated `tool_payload` JSON field (not the `content` column) so the record stays inspectable in the PocketBase engine room. **Tour 05** covers how the turn pipeline calls `Append`/`AppendOrigin` after the agent loop completes."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/conversation/conversation.go",
      "line": 134,
      "title": "12.5 — Context extraction: what the model sees",
      "description": "```go\nfunc RecentTurns(app core.App, conversationID string, limit int, after time.Time) ([]llm.Message, error)\n```\n\nThis single function is the gate between the full persistent record and what the model actually receives. It applies four filters deliberately:\n\n1. **Role** — only `user` and `assistant` turns. Tool rounds (`role='tool'`) are excluded: OpenAI-style APIs reject tool messages that do not follow their exact `assistant tool_calls` turn, and replaying stale tool output invites the model to act on it.\n2. **Empty content** — assistant turns that consist solely of tool calls have no content field. Excluding them keeps the context window clean.\n3. **Runtime origins** — turns tagged `uncommitted` or `check` are excluded so a fabrication the model made once is never replayed back as a pattern to imitate.\n4. **Compaction boundary** — when `after` is non-zero (from `CompactedThrough`), turns at or before it are excluded; the rolling summary covers that span instead.\n\nThe query returns newest-first (cheap with the rowid index); the function reverses with `slices.Backward` before returning so the caller gets chronological order ready to prepend to the model message list.\n\nAGENTS.md rule: *context is transparent — durable state lives in PocketBase collections; never hidden in-session state.*"
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/store/audit.go",
      "line": 14,
      "title": "12.6 — Audit: append-only, silent-fail by design",
      "description": "```go\nfunc Audit(app core.App, actor, action, target string, allowed bool, detail map[string]any)\n```\n\nThe audit log records every consequential write: tool invocations, model changes, owner-settings mutations, extension approvals. Three design choices are load-bearing:\n\n1. **Append-only** — `Audit` only ever creates new rows; nothing in this package updates or deletes audit records. The log is a permanent ledger.\n2. **Silent-fail** — all errors are swallowed (`_ = app.Save(rec)`). Auditing must never take the runtime down. A failed audit row is unfortunate; a crashed companion over a logging failure is not acceptable. This is the **only** intentionally silent path in the codebase.\n3. **Called after the successful write** — callers audit strictly after `app.Save` succeeds, never before. AGENTS.md states this explicitly: *audit strictly AFTER the successful write — the audit log must not record a mutation that did not persist.* A pre-audit of a write that then fails would record an event that did not happen.\n\nThe `actor` label (`\"owner\"`, `\"model\"`, `\"tasks\"`) tells the log who initiated the action; `allowed` records whether it was permitted (OS tool denials land here too)."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/store/owner_settings.go",
      "line": 47,
      "title": "12.7 — Owner settings: the only KV store",
      "description": "```go\nfunc SetOwnerSetting(app core.App, key, value string) error\n```\n\n`owner_settings` is Balaur's one key/value table for non-structured owner preferences: display name, timezone, soul avatar, and similar single-string values. `SetOwnerSetting` upserts a row with a **retry-once pattern** to handle the concurrent-insert race on the UNIQUE key index:\n\n1. Look up the existing row by key.\n2. If not found, create a new record; if found, update in place.\n3. If `app.Save` fails — a concurrent request inserted the row between the lookup and save — retry once. By the second attempt the row exists, so the retry always updates.\n\nThe **avatar rosters** (`SoulAvatars()`, `BalaurHeads()`) in this file are the single source of truth for selectable avatar keys and URLs. Web option builders and URL resolvers both iterate these slices — nothing else hardcodes avatar strings. `store` holds these because they are cross-cutting: the web layer, the head package, and the CLI all need them. This is exactly the three-caller rule (`audit.go` header: *helpers move here only when a third caller appears*).\n\nAGENTS.md rule: *single-flight / check-then-act on `app.Store()` or records uses an atomic primitive, never `GetOk`+`Set` or read-modify-write.*"
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/store/time.go",
      "line": 22,
      "title": "12.8 — Owner timezone: resolved per-call, no globals",
      "description": "```go\nfunc OwnerLocation(app core.App) *time.Location\n```\n\nAll period math in Balaur — recap days, week/month boundaries, cron tick alignment — is anchored to the owner's timezone, not UTC and not the server's system clock. `OwnerLocation` resolves that timezone on every call:\n\n1. Read `\"timezone\"` from `owner_settings`. If unset or the IANA name is invalid, fall back to `time.Local` (the box's system zone).\n2. Parse with `time.LoadLocation`. A typo in the settings value silently falls back rather than crashing cron jobs.\n\nThe per-call resolution is deliberate: **no global state**. A dashboard edit takes effect on the next cron tick without a restart. AGENTS.md rule: *persistent state resolved lazily — never module-level globals holding derived paths or config.*\n\n`PBTime` in the same file (`time.go` line 13) formats a `time.Time` the way PocketBase stores `DateTime` fields — it moved here on its third caller (recap, tasks, web) per the one-source-of-truth rule. Both helpers together make `internal/store/time.go` the single place for time-formatting concerns shared across packages."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/store/llm_settings.go",
      "line": 44,
      "title": "12.9 — What store is NOT: domain logic stays in its own package",
      "description": "```go\nfunc EnsureDefaultLLMConfig(app core.App, dataDir string) error\nfunc ListLLMModels(app core.App) ([]LLMConfig, error)\n```\n\n`internal/store` is the seam for **cross-cutting concerns only**: audit, owner settings, LLM config, and time formatting. The header comment states the rule precisely: *helpers move here only when a third caller appears.*\n\n`llm_settings.go` is a controlled exception that illustrates the boundary. LLM provider and model configuration is genuinely cross-cutting — the web layer, the CLI, the turn pipeline, and `main.go`'s startup all need to read or write it. So it lives in `store`.\n\nThe rule's negative case matters more: **domain logic must NOT route through store**. `internal/conversation`, `internal/knowledge`, `internal/tasks`, `internal/life`, `internal/recap`, `internal/heads`, `internal/ext`, `internal/self` all talk to PocketBase directly via `app.FindRecordsByFilter`, `app.Save`, etc. in their own packages. They are not hidden behind a store abstraction.\n\nThis is why PocketBase is hard to upgrade: over 20 files touch it directly. That is an accepted, honest cost of the design — the alternative (routing everything through store) would create a leaky mega-abstraction that violates KISS and YAGNI. AGENTS.md states it plainly: *new domain logic talks to PocketBase directly in its own package — do not route it through store.*\n\n**Tour 05** covers the turn pipeline that uses `store.ActiveLLMConfig` to resolve the model. **Tour 11** covers how the Kronk engine is selected after that resolution."
    }
  ]
}
